Using Time Data to forecast Train delay duration¶

The goal¶

Here Pythonatic will be using train data, namely a train departure Delay Duration (measured in seconds), and a Date & Time label for that departure to forecast future delay durations.

SARIMA¶

To make these forecasts Pythonatic will be using a model called SARIMA to make the delay forecasts. SARIMA stands for Seasonal Auto-Regressive Integrated Moving Average with factors and was built on previous simpler algorithms, ARMA which then enabled ARIMA to be built. These previous algorithms had less components.

SARIMA components¶

Below are the algorithm's components summarized:

  • Seasonal means the model will try to find 'seasonal' patterns and use them to help in forecasting. It could for example be helpful in finding patterns such as average delays being longer during rush hours or in weekdays as opposed to weekends.
  • Auto-Regressive means the model looks at the relationship between a given measurement and a few measurements close to it. This helps the model "see" how for example, previous delays might impact delays a a given amount of time later.
  • Integrated makes use of differencing of raw observations (e.g. subtracting an observation from an observation at the previous time step) in order to make the time series stationary.
  • Moving Average uses the dependency between an observation and a residual error from a moving average model applied to lagged observations.

Seasonality component¶

We decided to use SARIMA so we could investigate the seasonal patterns we noticed during data analysis, that some departure times seemed to have more potential for longer delays. That there was a visible difference between average delay durations during weekdays and during weekends.

Rush hours¶

In this case we'll be investigating patterns noticed throughout each day. We've researched different official business hours and decided to label each datapoint with a number symbolizing the day slice that train was departing on.

We sliced each day in 5 different parts defined around business rush hours:

  • 1 means the train was planning to depart during Early_Morning (00:00 - 05:59)
  • 2 means the train was planning to depart during Morning_Rush_Hour (06:00 - 09:59)
  • 3 means the train was planning to depart during Between_Rush_hours (10:00 - 14:59)
  • 4 means the train was planning to depart during Afternoon_Rush_hour (15:00 - 18:59)
  • 5 means the train was planning to depart during Night (19:00 - 24:00)

What we expect is that delays happen more often and for longer during our two defined Rush hours, Morning_Rush_Hour and Afternoon_Rush_hour

We can aggregate the delay data by these day slices to use it as our seasonality component with SARIMA. Later these day slices are also called Time_Group.

Consecutive day slices¶

I'll start by creating a column, "Time_Group_Day", that labels each day's slice differently. (i.e. instead of grouping all early mornings together I group early morning of day 1 separately from early morning of day 2.

Since there are 5 time groups per day and 31 days in january, this column will go from 1 to 155 (31*5).

  • 1 Early_Morning (00:00 - 05:59)
  • 2 Morning_Rush_Hour (06:00 - 09:59)
  • 3 Between_Rush_hours (10:00 - 14:59)
  • 4 Afternoon_Rush_hour (15:00 - 18:59)
  • 5 Night (19:00 - 24:00)

In other words Day 1 slices will go from 1 to 5 like above, Day 2 slices will go from 6 to 10, Day 3 from 11 to 15, etc. This way the process would be usable for any month with any length, or the whole year.

In [145]:
# Here I compute the consecutive day slices, using the index which is a train's planned departure time.
# I access the index's day component and multiply it by the number of desired slices, in this case 5.
# Then I add the number from the time group column to label it as the proper day slice
df['Time_Group_Day'] = df['Time_Group_Number'] + (df.index.day - df.index.day.min())*5

Time Group visual patterns¶

As you can see above even averaging the delay duration by day slice still leaves it very spiky, and it is difficult to visualize any patterns exactly. We investigated how we could visualize the different day slices along the plot but it would have taken too long to implement.

  • 1 Early_Morning (00:00 - 05:59)
  • 2 Morning_Rush_Hour (06:00 - 09:59)
  • 3 Between_Rush_hours (10:00 - 14:59)
  • 4 Afternoon_Rush_hour (15:00 - 18:59)
  • 5 Night (19:00 - 24:00)

However, knowing the first group is morning rush hour on January 1st already shows some patterns.

Starting from January 1st: Strangely while morning rush hour starts higher than between rush hours or afternoon rush hour, Night spikes somewhat dramatically. Then early morning and morning rush hour the next day have low average delays and between rush hours spikes, before lowering a bit during afternoon rush hour and going all the way down during night and early morning next day.

Just from these first few slices I cannot see a clearly repeating pattern, it just seems to spike sometimes. Perhaps with a better visualisation it would be possible to see some patterns.

Delay duration ranges¶

As you can see in the table above, the average delay per slice ranges from 2.6 seconds to 245 seconds (or ~4 minutes).

These average delay durations are incredibly low, presumably because most trains simply have very little to no delay. Even the maximum delay of 4 minutes is unlikely to affect much beyond specific situations such as having a very tight time window to transfer between trains.

As much as this is unlikely to be of use for Ordina employees we will nevertheless attempt a forecast using this data below.

SARIMA SETUP¶

Each of SARIMA's components are explicitly specified in the model as a parameter. A standard notation is used of ARIMA(p,d,q) where the parameters are substituted with integer values to quickly indicate the specific ARIMA model being used.

A value of 0 for any of these actually alters the exact model used. For example later in the code I will use a function called SARIMAX and simply not provide input for the eXogenous part, this makes it into SARIMA. The same can be applied to the rest of the parameters to get models such as simply AR.

The parameters (order) of the ARIMA model are defined as follows:

  • AR is p: The number of lag observations included in the model, also called the lag order.
  • I is d: The number of times that the raw observations are differenced, also called the degree of differencing.
  • MA is q: The size of the moving average window, also called the order of moving average.

Sarima then introduces seasonal versions (seasonal_order) of these along with a parameter defining seasonality:

  • seasonal_p: The number of lag observations included in the model, also called the lag order.
  • seasonal_d: The number of times that the raw observations are differenced, also called the degree of differencing.

  • seasonal_q: The size of the moving average window, also called the order of moving average.

  • seasonality: The number of rows between the observations it should compare. More specifically since we want to compare the first slice of a day to the first slice of the next day and the data aggregated by 5 types of time groups, there are 5 slices between the same type of group, so seasonality should be five.

In [164]:
# Due to rush hours slicing each day in 5 and data being aggregated into those slices
# I want to compare for example monday morning to tuesday morning to wednesday morning
seasonality = 5

Machine Learning - Time Series¶

Hyperparameter Random Searching¶

To maximize my models accuracy I will select my model's hyper parameters by randomly generating them in batches and selecting the best out of those batches.

Below I define how big I want the batches to be, and how many batches I want there to be.

In [165]:
# The inner loop will generate hyperparameter combinations and fit them this many times
batch_size = 20

# I will do this many batches and get the best scoring hyperparameter combination out of each one 
batches = 5

print("I will generate and fit hyperparameters combinations in {} batches of {}, choosing the best one every time.\nSARIMA will be fitted {} times in total.".format(batches, batch_size, batch_size*batches))

I will generate and fit hyperparameters combinations in 5 batches of 20, choosing the best one every time.
SARIMA will be fitted 100 times in total.

Hyperparameter + Score storage during Random search¶

Below I create two python lists: one to contain all scores and hyperparameters and one to contain the best one of each batch. Both are python lists that follow the same format.

Each element inside said lists contains another python list. These then contain the following elements:

  • The p,d,q parameters
  • The seasonal parameters = p,d,q,seasonality
  • The resulting aic score from fitting the model with these parameters (a lower aic score is better)
In [166]:
# This stores every single result from all batches together. Each element is a python list containing three elementsthe p,d,q parameters
all_results = []

# This contains the hyperparameters best score parameters from each batch.
top_scores = []

# This counts the number of times something went wrong during fitting that lead to results being discarded
exceptions = 0
In [167]:
# specify to ignore warning messages, as the model sometimes fails
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

Filtering broken results¶

During the loop you'll notice we filter out all aic scores under 700. We do this because during random searching the model sometimes broke but did not throw an exception. Because of this it technically worked, but outputted scores that were far too low. Visualization of these forecasts either failed or simply did not make sense

In [168]:
# Outer loop, runs 'batches' number of times to get the best paramaters from a given batch
for i in range(batches):
    
    # batch_of_results is python list where each element inside is a python list itself.
    # batch_of_results contains batch_size number of lists inside, each of those lists has 3 elements
    # those 3 elements are [pdq paramereters, seasonal pdq parameters, their score after fitting]
    batch_of_results = []
    
    # Inner loop, runs 'batch_size' number of times
    # Generates parameters randomly and fits them
    for j in range(batch_size):        
        
        # HYPERPARAMETER GENERATION
        # I generate each of the hyper parameters randomly between 0 and 6 inclusive
        # Using random parameters might lead to nonsensical algorithms which would lead to longer processing or weird scores
        p = random.randint(0, 6)
        d = random.randint(0, 6)
        q = random.randint(0, 6)

        seasonal_p = random.randint(0, 6)
        seasonal_d = random.randint(0, 6)
        seasonal_q = random.randint(0, 6)
        
        try:
            # I provide the sarimax model with the data, the p,d,q parameters and the seasonal parameters
            # I provide no exogenous parameters, so it is actually SARIMA
            mod = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(dfGroupie,
                                            order = (p, d, q),
                                            seasonal_order = (seasonal_p, seasonal_d, seasonal_q, seasonality),
                                            enforce_stationarity=False,
                                            enforce_invertibility=False)

            # Fit model to data according to hyperparameters defined in mod and store result
            results = mod.fit()
            
            if(results.aic > 700):
                # store the score in all score array
                batch_of_results.append(((p, d, q), (seasonal_p, seasonal_d, seasonal_q, seasonality), results))
                all_results.append(((p, d, q), (seasonal_p, seasonal_d, seasonal_q, seasonality), results))
                print('\nBatch {} of {} - Iteration {} of {}\nSARIMA{}x{}{} - AIC:{}'.format(i, batches-1, j, batch_size-1, (p, d, q), (seasonal_p, seasonal_d, seasonal_q), seasonality, results.aic))
            else:
                exceptions = exceptions + 1
                
        except:
            exceptions = exceptions + 1
            continue
    # Below I extract the best scores
    # I do this by sorting the third element (score) of the batch_of_results array because the first 2 elements are the parameters
    # sorted() then just sorts the batch_of_results array by score
    # finally I slice it and get the very best score (it's the lowest so it's the first one after sorting)
    top_scores.append(sorted(batch_of_results, key = lambda x: (x[2]).aic)[:1])

Best parameters random mutation¶

To try to improve these already good scores we've defined a function below called apply_small_changes()

It takes a python list of scores and makes small changes to the parameters to try to find better parameters.

We specifically chose to make a function because we noticed this process was almost indefinitely repeatable. Every time we used it we would find slightly better hyperparameters.

In the end we only use it once because the scores were already very close to eachother, making any improvement from further iterations minimal.

In [186]:
def apply_small_changes(scores, mutations):
    exceptions = 0
    mutated_results = []

    # Possible changes for hyperparameters, chosen randomly and weighted slightly towards making no change
    small_changes = [-1, 0, 0, 0, 1]

    # For each of the original top scores 
    for score_array in scores:
        score = score_array[0]
        #print('ORIGINAL {}x{}{} - AIC:{}'.format(score[0], score[1], seasonality, score[2].aic))

        # mutate this score slightly 5 times
        for j in range(mutations):
            
            # Randomly choose a number from the small changes list and add it to each parameter
            p = (score[0][0] + random.choice(small_changes))
            d = (score[0][1] + random.choice(small_changes))
            q = (score[0][2] + random.choice(small_changes))

            seasonal_p = (score[1][0] + random.choice(small_changes))
            seasonal_d = (score[1][1] + random.choice(small_changes))
            seasonal_q = (score[1][2] + random.choice(small_changes))

            # Test the newly mutated parameters
            try:
                mod = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(dfGroupie,
                                                order = (p, d, q),
                                                seasonal_order = (seasonal_p, seasonal_d, seasonal_q, seasonality),
                                                enforce_stationarity=False,
                                                enforce_invertibility=False)

                # Fit model to data using mutated parameters
                results = mod.fit()
                
                if(results.aic >= 1000):
                    # store the score in mutated_results list
                    mutated_results.append([(p, d, q), (seasonal_p, seasonal_d, seasonal_q, seasonality), results])
                    #print('SARIMA{}x{}{} - AIC:{}'.format((p, d, q), (seasonal_p, seasonal_d, seasonal_q), seasonality, results.aic))
                else:
                    exceptions = exceptions + 1
            except:
                exceptions = exceptions + 1
                continue
    print("Fitting mutated parameters failed {} times of the planned {}".format(exceptions, len(scores)*mutations))
    return(mutated_results)

Results analysis¶

From the graphs above you can see the model fit the data reasonably.

Normal Q-Q¶

The red line traced the data points appropriately which is a good sign, though you can see some points don't exactly fit the line to the left and particularly at the end of the line.

Correlogram¶

None of the points in the correlogram are outside of the light blue area which is a good sign. The first one is just the first observation so it correlates with itself and will always be very high in any graph.

Histogram¶

Here the green line is just a standard distribution line for reference. The bars represent the distribution of the data by lags defined by the model. Finally the orange line is how the model tried to fit a distribution to the data. You can see the orange line tends to the right at its highest point which fits better with the distribution of the data, as the blue bars are higher there.

plt.show()

Forecasting graph analysis¶

Above you can see a graph showing average train delay in seconds on the y axis, plotted over time for January. You can see that though the lines are very spiky, they actually only ever go from 0 to 250 seconds.

250 seconds being 4 minutes 10 seconds, we will be forecasting very small and likely unimpactful delays. This is probably caused by the data imbalance, taking an average delay for a given time period is likely to trend to very low delays as only a very small percentage of trains ever departs more than 5 minutes late.

Trends¶

Above you can see the forecast follows previously observed trends as the orange line is very close to the blue one. It peaks when the blue one peaks, but does skip some peaks when the blue line is very spiky.

It follows the general trend well however the grey area shows it has a high error margin, even going into negative values despite none of the values ever being negative.

Negative Error¶

For trains the delay being negative means it left early and so it happens almost never, but the model does not know this, it only 'sees' decimal values and their trends over time.

Mean squared error calculation¶

Here we calculate the mean squared error to measure the error margin using actual numbers.

In [194]:
delay_forecasted = pred.predicted_mean
delay_truth = dfGroupie['2016-01-20 05:28:00':]
delay_truth = delay_truth.squeeze()

# Compute the mean square error
mse = ((delay_forecasted - delay_truth) ** 2).mean()

print('The Mean Squared Error of our forecasts is {}'.format(round(mse, 2)))

The Mean Squared Error of our forecasts is 800.79

Well the average squared error is 800.79 which seems quite, however this does not tell us anything real so let's calculate its square root now.

In [195]:
math.sqrt(mse)
Out[195]:
28.298214120740564

Error Margin conclusion¶

Looking at its square root, on average this model will have an error margin of just 28.29 seconds. For a train's delay this is effectively nothing, so this error is practically negligible.

If we look at the forecasting graph again, such a small error margin makes sense as we're working with very small delays anyway.

Conclusion¶

Using this model we can predict the average delay of a specific part of a future day with a negligible error.

However many issues prevent us from making actual use of this model:

The data is unrepresentative of the real world:

  • The data imbalance caused by almost no train ever departing with a delay of 5 minutes or later, means the model will simply never predict a huge delay.
  • The data simply being out of date. 2016 train data is unlikely to be representative of the train infrastructure in 2022

Even if we had the data of 2022 it would likely still be imbalanced due to a lack of large delay data.

Taking the average delay duration per time group makes our model more accurate but is not very helpful. Particularly it cannot predict the large delays that actually impact travel.

Of course were we to try to predict large delays, we would quickly find that we lacked enough data for this, as the vast majority of trains simply don't have a very big delay.

Go or No Go¶

Sadly due to the reasons above we simply cannot trust these resuts enough for implementation.
